thread.title: The EU has given Theresa May 48 hours to save her Brexit deal
thread.title_full: The EU has given Theresa May 48 hours to save her Brexit deal - Business Insider

posts.author: Adam Payne
posts.title: The EU has given Theresa May 48 hours to save her Brexit deal
posts.text:
REUTERS/Hannah McKay
Theresa May faces a race against time to prevent Brexit talks from being delayed until 2018. EU tells Britain it must come up with a solution to the Irish border in 48 hours. May to hold talks with Irish government and DUP in an attempt to achieve "sufficient progress."
LONDON — Michel Barnier has informed EU member states that Britain has just 48 hours to agree on a potential deal on the first phase of Brexit talks for talks to move onto trade and transition before 2018.
The EU's chief Brexit negotiator has told European ambassadors that the UK government is trying to come up with a proposal on the Irish border that will satisfy both the DUP and the Irish government, the Guardian reports .
A last-minute meeting between representatives of the EU27 has been scheduled for Friday in case Theresa May is able to get both the DUP and Irish government on side with her plans.
Both parties have said that the prime minister must make key changes to what she is proposing on the Irish border before they can give their approval to a deal on the first phase of negotiations.
Irish Taoiseach Leo Varadkar said yesterday that he expects May to offer him a new deal on the Irish border today.
"Having consulted with people in London, [May] wants to come back to us with text tonight and tomorrow. And I expect to move forward as well — I want us to move forward if it’s possible next week," he said.
If Britain is unable to produce a potential agreement by Friday, then the EU will rule that "insufficient progress" has been made on the issues of citizens' rights, Britain's financial settlement, and the Irish border.
This would mean talks on future trade arrangements and any transition deal could not begin until 2018, something the UK government is determined to avoid given the increased uncertainty it would mean for British business.
A CBI survey conducted in last month found that 60% of firms based in Britain will trigger Brexit contingency plans in March if a transition deal isn't agreed. These plans would include moving staff abroad and slowing recruitment.
The EU has hinted that it might be prepared to hold an emergency summit in January or February of next year in order to speed up negotiations. However, this is not a chance the British side will want to take.
The Irish border issue turned from a headache into a crisis for May this past week after DUP leader Arlene Foster blocked the UK government's proposal for "regulatory alignment" between Northern Ireland and the EU after Brexit.
In practice, this would have major implications for Northern Ireland, as it would require it to stay as close as possible to EU rules in order to maintain seamless, free movement of goods and people across the border.
The DUP is adamant that it will not accept any deal that ties Northern Ireland to EU regulations and subsequently creates new trade barriers between Belfast and the rest of the UK.
The Republic insists that keeping the UK in the single market and customs union is the best way to avoid the return of a hard border. However, the UK government has pledged to remove Britain from both organisations.

At a signing ceremony on November 27 th , Canadian University Dubai represented by its President, Pr. Karim Chelli and Tn. Hj. Salleh Bin Kassim, Rector and CEO of UTMSPACE SERVICES SDN. BHD, a subsidiary of UTM (University Teknologi Malaysia) formalized a partnership agreement to launch its new twinning program with the Canadian University Dubai. 
The agreement ushers in the Canadian University Dubai’s strategy to expand beyond Dubai and to introduce Canadian education to the region fulfilling its vision to promote Canadian perspectives in learning, research, and application embedded in Canada’s culture of excellence in education and values. 
With the introduction of the Canadian based programs, students will have the opportunity to earn an internationally recognized degree within Malaysia or take advantage of the opportunity to transfer to the university’s Dubai campus or to one of its Canadian education partners comprised of a group of 24 Canadian education institutions representing Canada from coast to coast. 
Pr. Karim Chelli said, “The long-existing ties between our countries have highlighted the importance of our recent decision to formalize a strategy to expand beyond Dubai introducing the principles of Canadian education internationally. The signing of this agreement marks a milestone in our growth strategy and this project has been in planning for years and I am delighted to see our efforts and those of our partners in Malaysia begin to come to fruition.” 
He continued, “The importance of higher education remains as critical as ever particularly for the economic growth and development of all nations. The introduction of Canadian education into Malaysia allows it to continue to compete with the expanding global education landscape. The Canadian University Dubai’s expansion into the region will certainly increase our competitiveness and add another dimension to the quality of education in Malaysia and the region.” 
Tn. Hj. Salleh Bin Kassim, Rector and CEO of UTMSPACE SERVICES SDN said, “This project has been in planning for some time and it is one that we are happy to have been involved in alongside our partners; the internationally accredited Canadian University Dubai. As part of our strategy to continuously enhance learning opportunities for our future leaders in a globally evolving economy, the signing of the agreement and the anticipated beginning of the twinning program within our facilities demonstrates our commitment to elevate the choices available to our youth and to the improvement of our national economy. We look forward to welcoming Malaysian students and students of all nationalities from the region as well as the Canadian University’s faculty members and researchers." 
Scheduled to open September 2018, enrollment should begin with two of its Bachelor programs in Business Administration, with other programs slated to be introduced in the near future. The signing represents a monumental shift in the type of educational opportunities available to students in the region enhancing the education landscape in Malaysia. 
As such it will begin accepting applications of new students in the next academic year in 2018 for admission into its Bachelor of Business Administration in International Business and Bachelor of Business Administration in Marketing. 
Canadian University Dubai will be providing the programs’ faculty and curriculum and taking full ownership of the programs’ quality and standards guided by the rigorous standards set forth by the principles of Canadian education.

A painting of Jesus believed to be by Leonardo da Vinci that shattered auction records when it was sold for $450 million last month will go on display at the Louvre Abu Dhabi, the museum announced Wednesday on Twitter. 
The museum tweeted that "Da Vinci's Salvator Mundi is coming to #LouvreAbuDhabi," which was confirmed by Christie's, the auction house that handled the sale of the painting. Christie's declined to say whether the museum bought the painting. 
The New York Times reported Saudi Prince Bader bin Abdullah bin Mohammed bin Farhan al-Saud purchased the painting at the Nov. 15 auction. 
The painting, the title of which means "Savior of the World" in English, was the most expensive painting ever sold at auction. The previous record was Pablo Picasso's Les Femmes d'Alger, which sold for $179 million. 
The Louvre Abu Dhabi, which is affiliated with the Paris original, opened in November, costing more than $1.3 billion to construct. It has more than 600 artworks in its permanent collection.

posts.author: I_heart_Venice
posts.text:
Anyone that accepts payment of money for services (or barters the equivalent of money) must be registered with the local or state government (or both). All guests (both short and long term rentals) are supposed to be registered with the "questura" (central police station) within 48 hours of their arrival.
All money paid should have a corresponding fiscal receipt issued for the same amount. The fiscal receipts can be handwritten, but are supposed to correspond to specific criteria.
That being said, there is no "registration number" that need be displayed on the adverts for rentals, or on sites such as AirBnB or the other apartment rental portals, and the Italian fiscal agents have had several "sting" operations in the past few years where anywhere from several to dozens of previously undocumented rental properties come to light, meaning that any money taken until their discovery was undeclared, black-market earnings for the owners and managers.
It is becoming more difficult, and less common, but there are still new ones which may not follow the letter or spirit of current regulations and laws, and it is often very difficult to distinguish one from the other.
If upon inquiry about the city tax, an apartment owner says something "that is not necessary for this category of apartment" or something similar, it is probably not correctly registered, and thus most likely illegal.

A host of high-profile Experts, Researchers and Academics in the field of vocational education and inclusive employment are set to participate in the inaugural International Conference on Inclusive Employment and Occupational Learning 2017 (ICIEOL 2017), taking place in Dubai on December 10-11, 2017. 
The conference is sponsored by Dubai’s Community Development Authority (CDA) and organised by Qualifications House UK in collaboration with the Mohammed Bin Rashid Al Maktoum Knowledge Foundation (MBRF) to coincide with the International Day of Persons with Disabilities. The event is rooted in the “My Community... A City for Everyone” initiative, which seeks to make Dubai a friendlier city for people of determination and is aligned with the inclusive employment pillar of Dubai Disability strategy 2020 
ICIEOL 2017 aims to emphasize and spread awareness on the legislative framework supporting the inclusive employment of PWD on an international and local level. Additionally, it identifies and disseminates best practices in the area of inclusive employment for People of determination, discusses related challenges and gaps in the local market and advances solutions to bride these gaps. It also portrays successful employment stories and models. 
CDA’s Director General His Excellency Ahmed Julfar said: “The list of influential and renowned scientists, researchers and academics that have come forward to take part in the first-ever International Conference on Inclusive Employment and Occupational Learning reflects the global momentum building up to empower people of determination to play their role in society. Dubai has proven to be a trailblazer in this regard with the ambitious Dubai Strategy for People of Determination 2020, launched by His Highness Sheikh Hamdan Bin Mohammed Bin Rashid Al Maktoum, Crowne Prince of Dubai. 
“The conference will set out to develop the necessary strategies to promote the role of rehabilitation and training for this high-potential segment of society,” H.E. Julfar explained, adding: “It identifies the challenges associated with achieving an inclusive working environment for people of determination, all the while outlining the Community Development Authority’s leading role in awareness and advocacy on right of people of determination to work and participate actively in the economic development of the UAE” 
Meanwhile, Dr Hisham Al Saghbini, Group CEO at Qualifications House UK, will deliver a keynote speech at the session titled “Prospects of Employment Inclusion in the UAE”. Specialising in quantitative and qualitative research in education, Dr Al Saghbini brings more than 15 years of international experience in the sector, where he Created the WPPD – Work Passport for People with Determination. 
Commenting on the launch of the inaugural ICIEOL 2017, Dr Al Saghbini noted: “The conference offers the ideal platform for experts to come together and identify the biggest challenges surrounding vocational training and rehabilitation for people of determination, as well as to plan for a prosperous and inclusive future for the employment market. Furthermore, the research papers that will be presented and discussed at length here at the event will be published through the international digital library EBSCO.” 
Moreover, Dr Naji Al Mahdi, Chief of Qualifications and Awards in Dubai at the Knowledge and Human Development Authority (KHDA), will join a panel discussing the “Transition from Inclusive Education to Inclusive Employment”, along with CDA’s Social Inclusion Specialist Dr Hussain Ali Maseeh. 
Dr Muna Al Hamadi, Professor at Zayed University who has also worked as a Disability Social Care Specialist at CDA will address “Challenges to Inclusive Employment” in a panel discussion at the conference, while Dr David Holliman, Global CEO of UK-based Specialist Education Consultants Global (SECGLO), explores in his session the “Challenges for People of Determination in the UAE”. SECGLO offers a wide variety of courses, corporate training and consultancy services to educational institutions in both the private and public sectors. 
On a similar note, Harry Bundered, Director of the Institute of Training and Occupational Learning (IOTL), is set to lead a discussion in a panel titled “Occupational Learning Model for People with Determination”. Bundered specialises in occupational learning and how to empower people from different groups in the workplace. 
The International Conference on Inclusive Employment and Occupational Learning 2017 is the first-of-its-kind in the region. It consolidates efforts of human capital development in the UAE, chiefly related to the people of determination, by promoting the role of scientific research and employing its outputs to increase inclusive employment. 
The initiatives emanating from the conference will spring to action the strategies needed to sustain human resource development by capitalising on academic research and practical experience in the process of inclusive employment, and activating the role of smart technology in planning, implementing and evaluating its processes.

posts.author: AFP Relaxnews
posts.title: 8 tips to help your tree last the whole holiday season
posts.text:
| December 7, 2017 Spray the tree with water at room temperature before decorating it. 
For many people, the holiday season is synonymous with a freshly cut Christmas tree. Before decking it out in baubles and lights, here are a few ways to help keep a cut tree looking good for longer this holiday season. 
Let it breathe 
Once you’ve bought your tree, remove the net that bundles up its branches as soon as possible. The branches need to spread out and settle into place. This will also help prevent the tree from overheating. 
Ease it in 
Try not to expose the tree to quick changes in temperature. Get it used to indoor warmth progressively by standing it in a cool room on on a balcony for 24-48 hours. 
Give it a drink 
It is recommended to saw a little bit off the base of the tree and stand it in water for a few hours. 
Keep away from heat sources 
A tree next to an open fire is a beautiful sight, but it’s not so good for the tree. Any source of heat — like a radiator, an open fire, a bright light, a TV or a sunny window — will dry out the tree, causing it to lose its color and its needles. 
Stay sheltered 
A tree won’t appreciate being in a drafty place or somewhere where there’s a lot of coming and going. Drafts will dry out the tree and people brushing past will make it lose its needles. 
Spritz before decorating 
It is advisable to spray the tree with water at room temperature before decorating. 
Keep it quenched 
Keep the foot of the tree moist in a bucket filled with sand or by pouring a cup of water onto the base. 
No artificial snow 
Go easy or pass completely on fake snow, like snow spray, which tends to dry out tree branches.

posts.title: CMA examines heat networks
posts.text: CMA examines heat networks 7 December 2017 | 09:23am StockMarketWire.com - The Competition and Markets Authority is launching a comprehensive study into domestic heat networks to ensure households are getting a good deal. The CMA said: 'Heat networks - systems that heat multiple homes from one central source - currently supply about half a million UK homes through about 17,000 networks. 'They can also be more environmentally friendly than some other sources of heat, delivering lower carbon emissions and resulting in cost benefits to households. 'As a result, heat networks form an important part of Government strategy to reduce carbon and cut heating bills. 'The number of customers using heat networks is expected to grow significantly to around 20% of all households by 2030.' The CMA said that while heat networks may have these wider benefits, the sector is not currently subject to the same regulation as other forms of energy supply such as mains gas and electricity. The CMA is concerned that many customers, a large proportion of whom live in social housing, may be unable to easily switch suppliers or are locked into very long contracts - some for up to 25 years - and that there is a risk they may be paying too much or receiving a poor quality of service. The CMA is planning to examine three broad themes: - Whether customers are aware of the costs of heat networks both before and after moving into a property - Whether heat networks are natural monopolies and the impact of differing incentives for builders, operators and customers of heat networks - The prices, service quality and reliability of heat networks Story provided by StockMarketWire.com LATEST STOCK MARKET NEWS AND OFFERS Get the latest stock market and investment news, market wraps, promotions and more!
